				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Q. and A.: Peter J. Li on the Clash Over Eating Dogs in China</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Shaojie Huang			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-06-19T00:05:35+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 18, 2015 8:05 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 18, 2015 8:05 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/19/world/18sino-li02/18sino-li02-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/19/world/18sino-li02/18sino-li02-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/19/world/18sino-li02/18sino-li02-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003748538" width="592" height="395" alt="Dog meat for sale at a market in Yulin on Wednesday, ahead of this weekend&#039;s celebration of the summer solstice with banquets of dog meat and lychees."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Dog meat for sale at a market in Yulin on Wednesday, ahead of this weekend's celebration of the summer solstice with banquets of dog meat and lychees.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/18/q-and-a-peter-j-li-on-the-clash-over-eating-dogs-in-china/" data-title="Q. and A.: Peter J. Li on the Clash Over Eating Dogs in China" data-description="Peter J. Li, a China policy adviser with Humane Society International, discusses the conflict between those who defend dog eating as a Chinese cultural tradition and those who view dogs as cherished companions. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An estimated 10 million dogs are killed for food each year in China. About 10,000 are expected to be slaughtered as the <a title="Times video. " href="//www.nytimes.com/video/multimedia/100000002955656/dog-meat-festival-in-china-city-angers-some-animal-rights-activi.html">Yulin Summer Solstice Lychee and Dog Meat Festival</a> gets underway this weekend in the southern city of Yulin.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/17/blogs/17sino-li02/17sino-li02-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/17/blogs/17sino-li02/17sino-li02-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/17/blogs/17sino-li02/17sino-li02-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003746316" width="190" height="292" alt="Peter J. Li"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="292"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Peter J. Li</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Peter J. Li</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">However, <a title="Sinosphere post." href="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/dog-meat-festival-proceeds-despite-protesters/">opposition has been building</a> to what its supporters call a local culinary tradition. Within China, confrontations between dog meat traders and animal welfare advocates have occasionally <a title="China Economic Net article (in Chinese). " href="//fj.ce.cn/n02/201406/23/t20140623_1596838.shtml">turned violent</a>. Internationally, in advance of the Dog Meat Festival, Animals Asia Foundation released results of a four-year <a title="Findings at the Animals Asia website. " href="https://www.animalsasia.org/intl/media/news/news-archive/chinese-dog-meat-trade-uncovered.html">investigation</a> concluding that the unregulated dog meat trade was encouraging pet-snatching. On Twitter, celebrities including Ricky Gervais and Nikki Reed are throwing their weight behind a <a title="Campaign on Twitter." href="https://www.twitter.com/hashtag/StopYuLin2015?src=hash">#StopYuLin2015</a> campaign to end the festival. A <a title="Raise UR Paw petition (in English). " href="https://www.change.org/p/president-of-the-people-s-republic-of-china-stop-the-yulin-dog-meat-eating-festival">petition</a> on Change.org to pressure the Chinese government to take action has gathered more than one million signatures.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Peter J. Li, an associate professor of East Asian politics at the University of Houston-Downtown and a China policy adviser with Humane Society International, has studied and <a title="Book containing Professor Li's work at the University of Chicago Press. " href="//press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/I/bo14398472.html">written</a> about animal protection and wildlife conservation in China for the past 15 years. In an interview, he discussed dog eating in China and the conflict between those who defend the practice as part of their cultural heritage and those who increasingly view dogs as cherished companions. Excerpts follow: <span id="more-32936"></span></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How did the Yulin Dog Meat Festival get started?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The festival was started by the cityâs dog meat traders in 2009-2010. The local officials of Yulin are <a title="Sinosphere post." href="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/17/city-aims-to-play-down-its-dog-meat-festival/">keeping their distance now</a>, because they seem to realize that such a festival is a liability to the city&#8217;s reputation. They were initially enthusiastic supporters of the event, thinking, ironically, it would help promote Yulinâs image as a tourist destination for lychee and dog meat.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/19/world/18sino-li01/18sino-li01-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/19/world/18sino-li01/18sino-li01-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/19/world/18sino-li01/18sino-li01-blog480.jpg" id="100000003748368" width="480" height="320" alt="Newly arrived dogs for the meat trade in Yulin, on May 25. The truck&#039;s driver said they had traveled about 800 miles, from Sichuan Province."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Newly arrived dogs for the meat trade in Yulin, on May 25. The truck's driver said they had traveled about 800 miles, from Sichuan Province.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Humane Society International, via Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>But instead, Yulin has become a battleground between those who want dog eating stopped and those who want it to continue. Do you expect more confrontations? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I was in Yulin in late May, I sat down with five dog meat traders. They said that their business had been affected by the nationwide protests. One said, &#8220;We&#8217;re prepared to fight back this year.&#8221; A confrontation between the dog meat traders and the protesters is unavoidable. Animal protection activists and others who have lost dogs to dog thieves and who are concerned about the risks of rabies outbreaks are converging in Yulin, for the fourth year since 2010. Activists started going to Yulin in great numbers in 2012. Animal rescue volunteers will also be there. We&#8217;re likely to see extortion against the rescue people as happened last year, when dog meat traders brutalized dogs in order to fetch high prices from the rescue people.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong> You&#8217;ve written that China slaughters 48.3 million cattle and 716 million pigs a year. By comparison, dog eating is rather insignificant. Why do you think it has attracted so much attention?<br />
</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The number of dogs slaughtered and consumed is insignificant. But this fact has important policy implications.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The impact of shutting down the dog meat trade would not be remotely significant for the Chinese economy. Yulin is a major agricultural region and one of the most important pig farming regions in Guangxi [Zhuang Autonomous Region]. Stopping pig farming there would hurt the local economy. Stopping the dog meat trade would not.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why has the debate over eating dogs become so intense, compared with 20 or 30 years ago?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Animal welfare was a new concept in China back in the early 1980s. The country didn&#8217;t have an officially registered animal welfare advocacy group until 1992, when the China Small Animal Protection Association was founded. There have been clashes between animal lovers and dog meat traders since the early 2000s.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong> What&#8217;s at stake in this debate?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A lot. This is more than an animal welfare issue. This is a matter of public health as well. After long-distance transport, most of the dogs are sick, dying or already dead. Skin problems are common. These are serious food safety problems and public health hazards.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Zoonotic diseases are another public health concern. Rabies can break out among traders after handling a large number of dogs with compromised health. My investigation found that most dog meat traders have not been vaccinated for rabies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Guangxi is among the five top provinces in terms of the number of human rabies cases in China. Most of the cases in Guangxi <a title="163.com article (in Chinese). " href="//gx.news.163.com/07/0102/14/33RCB62S006300CU.html">have been reported in Yulin</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is also about stopping the theft of pets.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/18/world/17SINO-LI/17SINO-LI-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/18/world/17SINO-LI/17SINO-LI-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/18/world/17SINO-LI/17SINO-LI-blog480.jpg" id="100000003746310" width="480" height="320" alt="Dogs at a slaughterhouse in Yulin."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Dogs at a slaughterhouse in Yulin.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Humane Society International, via Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Many people, when they hear of dog meat, think of ethnic Koreans in northeastern China and people from Guangdong Province in the south. But you&#8217;re saying it&#8217;s everywhere in China?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dog eating exists everywhere in China. Even in Tibet or ethnic Tibetan regions, dog eating is practiced by Han Chinese. However, dog eating, in terms of the volume of consumption, is concentrated in two regions. In Guangdong and Guangxi in the south, at least 65 percent of the 10 million slaughtered dogs are consumed in this region. Jilin in northeast China, where ethnic Koreans concentrate, is China&#8217;s second-largest dog meat market. The third region where dog eating is common is around Peixian in Jiangsu and nearby regions in Shandong.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But dog meat is not a daily food for the average Chinese. It&#8217;s not a food that is typically prepared in one&#8217;s own kitchen, like pork or chicken.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>You&#8217;ve been to Yulin during the Dog Meat Festival, and you traveled there last month. What did you see? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#8217;ve been to Yulin three times. I went there twice last year including on the summer solstice day. I went back to Yulin in late May as a representative of Humane Society International to investigate if Yulin was any different. Dogs were being shipped to Yulin from different parts of the country. I saw a truck with some 1,000 dogs from Sichuan being unloaded to slaughterhouses. Unlike in the past, when you would see big slaughter operations, I saw smaller operations scattered in different parts of the city. I went to two slaughterhouses. What I saw were terrified small dogs, typical of pet dogs in China, and cages of cats, many wearing collars, a sign of stolen household pets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The dogs and cats I saw were sick. The owners of the slaughterhouses admitted that the dogs and cats did not have quarantine inspection certificates as required by the Ministry of Agriculture. They also said the local animal health inspectors never visit to check the health of the animals they slaughter.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>But the local government is doing something. Last year, it banned killing dogs in the open, following outcries over animal cruelty, and any advertising using the words âdog meat.â Has that affected Yulin&#8217;s dog meat business? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The measures taken by the Yulin authorities last year did make life difficult for the traders, according to the ones I interviewed. They also said that protesters have made their lives difficult over the past four years, and that their children will definitely not carry on their profession.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet the Dog Meat Festival will surely take place again this year.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Yulin&#8217;s food and drug administration officials have promised to crack down on the festival this year, according to <a title="An Xiang's blog (in Chinese)." href="//blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_7cb32c0b0102vh6e.html">An Xiang</a>, a Beijing-based lawyer and expert on China&#8217;s animal protection laws, who filed a petition in March for Yulin to make public information on how it regulates dog meat production. Do you think there will be a crackdown this year in Yulin? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That&#8217;s an open question.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">According to Agriculture Ministry regulations on the transprovincial transport of live dogs and cats, every animal must have an individual quarantine inspection certificate. The dog meat traders either cannot produce such certificates, or they produce one certificate for all the dogs on board, or they produce fraudulent documents.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The question for Yulin is this: Has the city&#8217;s animal disease control office checked if the trucks carrying dogs and cats to Yulin have ever produced the required documents? If they have, then the Yulin authorities should release copies of those documents to the public.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If the authorities have never required the documents, then it is they who have violated national government policy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I believe the Yulin authorities are in hot water now. I believe the legal team led by An Xiang knows what to do next. Let&#8217;s see.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>As Chinese dog rescuers stigmatize dog eating, they have also come under scrutiny for what their critics call irrational behavior. Last year, activists transported hundreds of dogs they had bought from traders in Yulin without the required quarantine certificates, <a title="Beijing News article (in Chinese)." href="//news.qq.com/a/20140625/004756.htm">according to The Beijing News</a>. Dog traders accused them of double standards. </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was a misguided act, having no long-term impact on Yulin&#8217;s or the country&#8217;s dog meat industry. Worse still, this encouraged extortion by the traders, as we saw last year, and made the rescue people look irrational.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">However, since the Yulin authorities failed to stop those same dogs from entering the city without certificates, it was the Yulin authorities who violated the national government policy in the first place.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Are public attitudes changing toward dog eating in China?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yes. China <a title="National Bureau of Statistics of China (in Chinese)." href="//data.stats.gov.cn/visualchart/view?c=01">passed the threshold of 50 percent urbanization</a> in 2011. Last year, some 54 percent of the people lived in urban areas. The urban value system which sees dogs and cats as companions is becoming more dominant while the more traditional and rural value system that sees animals as tools and sources of income is being challenged.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong> But what you call an effect of urbanization some view as the influence of the West. Dog meat promoters have accused Chinese activists of introducing a harmful Western ideology into China. Are you concerned that this might attract hostility toward organizations like Humane Society International and Animals Asia? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Opposition to eating dog meat began with the Chinese themselves. The bond between companion animals and humans is not Western. It&#8217;s a transcultural phenomenon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the dog meat trade, international NGOs are on the side of Chinese forces for food safety, public health, private property protection and China&#8217;s reputation as a modern and progressive country. These are also the objectives of the Chinese government. Therefore, international NGOs like Humane Society International are on the side of the Chinese government.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I believe the government has much to gain by having a clear vision of who is its ally and who is its true opponent. Humane Society International will always support China&#8217;s progress in animal protection and other efforts in the interest of public safety. It will always oppose practices that brutalize animals and endanger human welfare.</p>
	</div>
